               <history>
                  <origin><!--Complex date:  markup manually-->
                     <origDate calendar="Gregorian" notAfter="1210" notBefore="1190">12th century, late or 13th century, early</origDate>
                     <origPlace cert="low">

                        <country key="place_1000140">Syria</country> (?)</origPlace><note> A Melkite
                        (an Arabic-speaking Greek Orthodox) area is suggested by the style of
                        script, decoration and the Arabic note on the margin of the other folio in
                        the US.</note></origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>The manuscript leaf bears notes in pencil on the lower left corner of fol.
                        1r, which may refer to a sale: “Greek XIII 3. 10. 0”, the ordinal indicating
                        the century, the numeral, perhaps, a price. Number “3” is  written in pencil
                        on the top right corner of fol. 1r.</p>
                     <p>The manuscript leaf was given to the Bodleian Library by <persName key="person_311">F. E. Norris</persName> in
                        1952, recorded in an ex-libris glued to the upper pastedown. Oval stamp of
                        the Bodleian Library on right margin of fol. 1r.</p>
                     <p>The photograph was obtained by exchange from Prof. Harold Willoughby
                        (1890-1962) in September 1954, as recorded in pencil on the lower margin of
                        fol. 2r. Prof. Willoughby bought the leaf in 1935 from J. Tregaskis and Son,
                        London: <title type="sub">Caxton Head Catalogue 1013, no. 11</title>. A
                        cutting from the catalogue is glued to the upper pastedown, describing the
                        leaf as containing “Marginal notes in Arabic”. It specifies a price of £3.
                        Cf. S. De Ricciand W. J. Wilson, <title type="sub">Census of Medieval and
                           Renaissance Manuscripts in the United States and Canada</title>, 3 vols.,
                        New York, 1935–40, II, <ref target="https://archive.org/details/censusofmedieval0002ricc/page/2283/mode/1up">p. 2284 </ref>(addenda to p. 670).</p>
                     <p>The leaf, formerly in the collection of Harold Willoghby, is now owned by
                        Bryan Blakemore of Springfield, Illinois, who obtained it form two former
                        students—an elderly couple — who reported purchasing it at a local auction
                        gallery in 2008 for around $20.</p>
                  </provenance>


               </history>
